# Project Title

Stochastic Surgery Schedules
Building AI course project

## Summary

We have predictions of how long a surgery is expected to take from a sample of 500,000 surgeries in a state hosptial system. We know both the planned time and the actual time.
Using a machine learning technique, such as random forest, we can predict how long a surgery will take given charactreristics of the patient, such as age, race, BMI, 
whether the patient is a smoker or not, and other metriocs. We also use categories of the years since medical graduation as an estimate of the skill of the surgeon.

Now that we have a prediction of how long the surgery will take for this patient and surgeon, schedule the surgery in a rolling month-long window. This can be addressed as 
a version of the general assignment problem using optimimization technique. However, traditional optimization does not take into account random events such as the operating
room (OR) is not yet cleaned for a new  surgery, hospital transport is dealyed in delivering the patient to the OR, the anathesilogist is not yet in the OR, or other unforseen event.

How do we create a schedule that accommodates these random occurences of delay?

## Background

This project was proposed to the National Institues of Health (NIH) for funding. Although the review team thought well of the machine learning surgery time predctions phase, and
commented that being able to produce a roughly month-long surgery schedule, the team was critical of the optimizatrion phase. The team thought that phase did not accommodate events 
that extend the actual time of a surgery such as the OR not being ready to accept a new patient, or a patient not at the OR due to delay in transport to the OR.


## How is it used?

The solution, an AI-produced schedule of surgeries, will replace the block scheduling of surgeries used in most hospitals. The schedule will replace the human-created schedule.


## Data sources and AI methods
The 500,000 recored surgery data will be provided by the Univeristy of Missouri hospital system. A smaller proof-of-concept (POC) dataset was provided by St. Vincent hospital, Indianapolis, Indiana.
The random forest machine learning technique gave good results on the POC data and will be used with the University Missouri hospital data.
The assignment algorithm is written in AMPL and presented to a publicly available mixed integer solver. This would be a first layer in a neural network
It is not yet clear how to handle the stochastic events that limit the current assignment algorithm, perhaps simulated annealing in a hidden layer.

## Challenges

The current solution does not take into account random events that effect the actual surgery times 
## What next?

Given a plausible solution to the stochastic times a surgery may take, we will publish the results in an appropriate journal and make the AI and assignment code available to the public

